{"parse":{"title":"The Bristol Art Library","pageid":11302196,"revid":814583655,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Tbal1.jpeg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/b/b0/Tbal1.jpeg/220px-Tbal1.jpeg\" width=\"220\" height=\"165\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/b/b0/Tbal1.jpeg/330px-Tbal1.jpeg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/b/b0/Tbal1.jpeg/440px-Tbal1.jpeg 2x\" data-file-width=\"482\" data-file-height=\"361\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Tbal1.jpeg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>The Bristol Art Library</div></div></div>\n<p><b>The Bristol Art Library</b> (TBAL) is an art and performance project created in 1998 by British artist Annabel Other. It consists of handmade books in a library the size of a suitcase.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=The_Bristol_Art_Library&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The project was devised as a protest at the closure of the original Bristol Art Library.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\nThe library consists of handmade identically-bound books on a wide range subjects produced by individual contributors from all areas of the arts and sciences, each catalogued according to the Dewey Decimal System. The books are contained within a small wooden cabinet and made available when Other \"performs\" the library in the guise of the Head Librarian. Although TBAL is primarily an artistic endeavour, it borrows the rhetoric of, and operates as a public institution, with affiliations to official library organisations worldwide. Readers must fill in appropriate application forms, and adhere to strict library rules whereupon the books can be read using a reader's ticket whenever the library is open for lending.\n</p><p>Membership is free. Friends of The Bristol Art Library (FOTBAL) can sit on a special cushion when reading books, and receive the library's internal newsletter. Assistant librarians attend training sessions led by the Head Librarian including book-stamping and shush-ing techniques. TBAL has a gift shop selling tea towels, bookmarks, and postcards. The library travels from venue to venue in an old-fashioned hand-pulled shopping trolley.\n</p><p>The Bristol Art Library officially opened its doors in New York at <a href=\"/wiki/Printed_Matter,_Inc\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Printed Matter, Inc\">Printed Matter, Inc</a> in 1998 (it lent its first book to an air hostess during the flight from London to New York). Since then, TBAL has toured worldwide to over 200 venues and events including <a href=\"/wiki/Metropolitan_Museum_of_Art\" title=\"Metropolitan Museum of Art\">Metropolitan Museum of Art</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Museum_of_Jurassic_Technology\" title=\"Museum of Jurassic Technology\">Museum of Jurassic Technology</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Harvard_University\" title=\"Harvard University\">Harvard University</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/BALTIC_Centre_for_Contemporary_Art\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"BALTIC Centre for Contemporary Art\">BALTIC Centre for Contemporary Art</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/De_La_Warr_Pavilion\" title=\"De La Warr Pavilion\">De La Warr Pavilion</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Glastonbury_Festival\" title=\"Glastonbury Festival\">Glastonbury Festival</a>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> <a href=\"/wiki/Hay_Festival\" title=\"Hay Festival\">Hay Festival</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/WOMAD\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"WOMAD\">WOMAD</a>, and toured extensively in the USA, Poland and Japan. It has a growing membership of over 11,000 and houses in excess of 250 books.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=The_Bristol_Art_Library&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">\"Library and Information News at Exeter\", The Line, issue 10, June 2000, <a href=\"/wiki/University_of_Exeter\" title=\"University of Exeter\">University of Exeter</a>.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Play 'shop' with library collection at St Ives festival, <i>Western Morning News</i>, Plymouth, August 26, 1999</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Poetry &amp; Words at Glastonbury (archive) <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://poetryandwordsblog.wordpress.com/tag/annabel-other/\">\"</a> Retrieved 6 December 2016.</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"External_links\">External links</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=The_Bristol_Art_Library&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: External links\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://vimeo.com/39005078\">The Head Librarian - Channel 4 short-film about The Bristol Art Library</